Do not use sed, awk, or direct shell commands to edit files. Only use the provided write_to_file or apply_diff tools for modifying code.

# Backlog Management Rules

## Directory Structure
- All backlog items are stored in `backlog/` directory
- `backlog/index.md` is the master index - always check this first
- Individual items are in `backlog/backlog-{priority}-{NNN}.md`

## Priority Levels
- CRIT: Critical (affects core functionality)
- HIGH: High priority (reliability & robustness)
- MED: Medium priority (code quality & maintainability)
- LOW: Low priority (cosmetic & nice-to-have)

## Status Values
- PROPOSED: New item, not yet started
- IN_PROGRESS: Currently being worked on
- COMPLETED: Finished and merged

## Adding New Backlog Items
1. Check `backlog/index.md` for the next available ID number
2. Create new file: `backlog/backlog-{priority}-{NNN}.md`
3. Use `backlog/TEMPLATE.md` as the template
4. Add entry to the index table in `backlog/index.md`

## File Naming Convention
- Critical: `backlog-crit-XXX.md` (e.g., backlog-crit-001.md)
- High: `backlog-high-XXX.md` (e.g., backlog-high-001.md)
- Medium: `backlog-med-XXX.md` (e.g., backlog-med-001.md)
- Low: `backlog-low-XXX.md` (e.g., backlog-low-001.md)

## Working on Backlog Items
1. Always reference backlog/index.md to understand priorities
2. Update item status to IN_PROGRESS when starting work
3. Include backlog item ID in commit messages
4. Update item status to COMPLETED when merged

## Before Starting Any Task
- Check `backlog/index.md` to understand current priorities
- Review related backlog items for context
